Honoring a promise. This is a negative review and I'm not pulling punches. Brace yourself.
Review for
>Chances
by PhazedOut
Biggest problem is that there's no story here. The stakes are non-existent and the conflict isn't compelling. You try to explain in chapter 3 that Jason is hesitant to admit his feelings because he doesn't want to lose his friend if Jennifer doesn't reciprocate, but you also tell us that she does at the end of chapter two (if you somehow couldn't figure that out in chapter one) so there's no tension.
What's obnoxious about the confession scene is that it's initiated (forced) by Jennifer, when it NEEDS to be initiated by Jason. As a result, he only says he's fallen for her when he's sure he has nothing to lose. He doesn't grow as a person from the experience, and he's not taking any risks, so there's no internal payoff. It's a toothless resolution to an already underwhelming conflict.
Another problem is just how much fluff there is in your prose. Bulky dialogue tags, repetition of ideas and descriptions, and filler words only serve to bog down the pacing. I found myself skipping to the dialogue because nothing outside of it is that important to understanding what's going on. Less is more.
You wrote golden irises to describe Jennifer's eyes twice in consecutive paragraphs, and you used "poke" and "prod" in the beginning like they were going out of style.
The dialogue in chapter 3 needs a clean up, there's a lot of grammar errors, specifically in where you place punctuation marks.
The one good thing I'll say is that there's decent chemistry between Jason and Jennifer. I liked their banter in chapters 1 and 4.
>“Me and you, we’ve been friends for years. You’re important to me and I wanted to make sure to capture that.”
This is line is a gem. It captures the kind of warmth and emotional intimacy that acts as the foundation for these kinds of stories.
